<br>
When I was a little kid, I was brought up Jewish (mom was jewish dad was not). I went to an elementary school in a low income area in the early 80s before politcal correctness and anal retentive forms of diversity were prevalent. I saw all this hype about Xmas and was always like "well what about MY holiday, Hanukah?" ... <br>
<br>
Well as time went by, my parents got divorced. My dad got custody of me and met a woman and eventually we all moved in together (I was about 8-9 yrs old at this time). Well, this woman was not Jewish and was very much christian of some sort. I still got my hanukah, but also got a christmas. This was all confusing to me, albeit super cool because I got gifts from both occasions.<br>
<br>
As time went on, we abandoned the whole hanukah thing (which was more or less what I was raised on), and we took up Xmas full time. Except for a couple years in my childhood when I was forced to goto hebrew sunday school (which I hated immensely), practicing a religion outside of giftgiving in december was NEVER forced on me. <br>
<br>
Mixed signals? Yes. <br>
<br>
Ok fast forward many years to the present day. Lets clarify a couple things....please think about these points from an objective standpoint!<br>
<br>
1. Christmas in the USA/Canada (and probably most of the western world) is a festive holiday there for people to spend lots of money on each other. The TRUE meaning of the day, the celebration of the birth of Jesus Christ, is LOST! Nobody, well probably 95% of people do not even think about this, they just put up a tree, decorate it, goto parties and eat and drink lots, then on xmas day give presents.<br>
<br>
2. Hanukah, same thing, is a reason for liberal jewish families to shower thier children with gifts, up until age 13. Hanukah, is the festival of lights which is celebration of some burned out temple that only had enough oil to burn a light 1 day, but somehow it lasted 8 days. This isnt even the holiest jewish holiday, but since it falls near xmas, it all gets lumped into the 'holiday season' and many gifts are given.<br>
<br>
Ok this all said, if someone says Happy Holidays or Merry Xmas to me, its a good thing. It simply is someone wishing me well. Sly is right, they arent saying "praise jesus blah blah blah". <br>
<br>
In God we Trust, One nation under god, etc etc. Though upon inception of these sayings, it was meant as a clear cut reference to christian god, does not really hold that same meaning today. At least to me it doesnt. The word "god" nowadays is more of a reference to whatever higher being you believe in personally, in whatever form or faith you see. <br>
<br>
For the most part, Americans are not a very religious culture, we say a lot of things that could be INTERPRETED religiously, ie Bless you when you sneeze, merry xmas, etc. Those things really are nothing more than our own way of wishing someone well. Nothing more, nothing less.<br>
<br>
Lots more that can be said on this topic but its real late so Ill stop =p<br>
